correctedStatement:
CONFIRMED by primary source (github.com/aradzie/keybr.com). In GuidedLesson.update() in packages/keybr-lesson/lib/guided.ts, after the minimum/maximum alphabet-size requirements are satisfied, a new (not-yet-confident) letter is included only when EVERY currently-included key clears the confidence gate, and which confidence is used depends on the recoverKeys setting:

  if (recoverKeys) {
    if (includedKeys.every((key) => (key.confidence ?? 0) >= 1)) { lessonKeys.include(...); }   // "all previous keys are now above the target speed"
  } else {
    if (includedKeys.every((key) => (key.bestConfidence ?? 0) >= 1)) { lessonKeys.include(...); } // "all previous keys were once above the target speed"
  }

recoverKeys defaults to FALSE — packages/keybr-lesson/lib/settings.ts: recoverKeys: booleanProp("lesson.guided.recoverKeys", false). So by default the gate uses bestConfidence (each key's BEST/historical confidence from its best-ever time), meaning each previous key only had to reach the target speed ONCE; with recoverKeys ON the gate uses live confidence, so all previous keys must be above target speed right now. Confidence is target-relative: confidence = speedToTime(targetSpeed) / timeToType (packages/keybr-lesson/lib/target.ts), so confidence ≥ 1 means your time-per-char ≤ target time, i.e. your speed ≥ target speed; bestConfidence is computed from bestTimeToType (your best-ever time) in packages/keybr-lesson/lib/key.ts. The default targetSpeed prop is 175 (settings.ts), and is user-configurable.

Two precisions to add to the bare claim (it is correct, but slightly understates the logic): (1) Before the every() gate runs, a separate per-iteration check unconditionally re-includes any individual key the user has ALREADY mastered: `if ((lessonKey.bestConfidence ?? 0) >= 1) { lessonKeys.include(...); }` ("Must include all confident keys"). So the every()-gate is specifically what unlocks the NEXT not-yet-confident letter. (2) The gate only applies once the included set has reached the configured maximum alphabet size; below the minimum (6 keys) keys are force-added regardless of confidence. After updating inclusion, the lesson then focuses on the weakest included key whose confidence (bestConfidence when recoverKeys off, live confidence when on) is < 1.

The repo's own unit test (packages/keybr-lesson/lib/guided.test.ts) proves the distinction: with previous keys at current-confidence 0.9 but bestConfidence 1, recoverKeys OFF unlocks a new key (result "ABCDEF[G]J") while recoverKeys ON unlocks nothing and re-focuses the weakest old key (result "[A]BCDEFJ"). The test groups are literally named "all previous keys are now above the target speed" vs "all previous keys were once above the target speed".
